{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569029"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:24:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:24:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21702"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21702"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.17,0.03,0.53,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104624"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14571"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86971"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"36822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104624"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with lower abdominal pain and vaginal spotting. She is six weeks pregnant with her first pregnancy. She has not yet had any ultrasounds or blood tests performed. Her menstrual cycles are regular at 28 days. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender, with no signs of peritonism. Speculum examination reveals a closed cervix with a small amount of old blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a serum beta-human chorionic gonadotropin of 6,000 IU/L. Transvaginal ultrasound shows an intrauterine gestational sac 18mm with crown-rump length of 5 mm and no detectable fetal heartbeat.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suction D\u0026C","Misoprostol","Methotrexate","Repeat ultrasound in 7 days","Repeat ultrasound in 48 hours"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features concerning for early pregnancy loss, but which do not yet meet diagnostic criteria. As recognised by the RACGP, a non-viable pregnancy is defined as one that meets any of the following criteria: no fetal heart activity for 30 second period in an embryo with crown-rump length \u22657 mm; no live fetus visible with a mean sac diameter \u226525 mm. This patient\u0027s findings (crown-rump length of 5 mm without cardiac activity) do not yet meet these criteria, necessitating a follow-up scan in 7 days. This conservative approach prevents inadvertent termination of potentially viable pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in 7 days\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This interval allows sufficient time for a viable pregnancy to demonstrate growth and cardiac activity, while also allowing definitive diagnosis of pregnancy failure if no progression occurs. A single ultrasound can be used to diagnose miscarriage when the mean sac diameter \u226525 mm and crown-rump length \u22657 mm without fetal heart rate. When measurements are below these thresholds (as in this case), a repeat ultrasound is necessary to ensure that the scan is not simply too early to detect a viable pregnancy, as some women may incorrectly date their pregnancy due to irregular periods or other factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary and not helpful in this scenario. It would be appropriate if the HCG \u22652000 and there is no intrauterine pregnancy seen and there are no other abnormal findings on the scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate at this stage as pregnancy failure has not been definitively diagnosed. Medical management should only be initiated once strict diagnostic criteria for pregnancy failure have been met.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuction D\u0026amp;C\u003C/strong\u003E carries the risk of terminating a potentially viable pregnancy and should only be performed once pregnancy failure is confirmed. It would be an option after confirmation of pregnancy failure if the patient prefers surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is used for ectopic pregnancy management and is contraindicated here as there is a confirmed intrauterine pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound findings must meet strict criteria before diagnosing early pregnancy loss to avoid inadvertent termination of viable pregnancies.","A crown-rump length \u003C7mm without cardiac activity requires repeat ultrasound in 7 days before confirming pregnancy loss.","Serial ultrasounds and quantitative beta-hCG measurements help differentiate between early pregnancy loss and early viable pregnancy."],"references":["NICE. Ectopic pregnancy and miscarriage: diagnosis and initial management. In: NICE guideline [NG126] [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng126","Breeze C. Early pregnancy bleeding. Aust Fam Physician. 2016;45(5):283-286. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/7dd1ab15-098e-44f8-8698-4930617c2efc/Early-pregnancy-bleeding.aspx#:~:text=A%20non%2Dviable%20pregnancy%20is,period%20of%20observation%20of%20at","SA Health. Bleeding \u0026 Pain in Early Pregnancy. Ectopic Pregnancy, Miscarriage \u0026 PUL. In: South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline [online]. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/clinical+resources/clinical+programs+and+practice+guidelines/womens+and+babies+health/perinatal/perinatal+practice+guidelines/perinatal+practice+guidelines","https://www.asum.com.au/files/public/SoP/curver/Obs-Gynae/Guidelines-for-the-Performance-of-First-Trimester-Ultrasound.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86971"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86971"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-03T12:05:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-03T13:34:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14571"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104624"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ud